    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks for that. we don't have a full heap profiler with a GUI available on the target hardware, so i'm mostly stuck with serial logs and manual instrumentation. i've tried adding some counters to our custom pool allocators, which shows the total allocated bytes creeping up, but it's hard to tell which specific object type or subsystem is responsible. \n\nhow can i narrow this down using just log-based instrumentation? specifically, if i see a steady upward trend in a specific memory pool, what are some ways to trace that back to the actual call site without crashing the system?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Instrument your memory pool allocator to log the call stack (or at least the function return address) upon every allocation request, tagging it with a unique ID for that allocation. When you see the specific pool growing, filter your logs for allocations originating from that pool over time. By comparing the frequency and timestamps of these logged allocations against your operational events, you can correlate the memory creep with specific system functions that are likely not cleaning up after themselves.",
      "source": "target",
